er.\n\nWidespread  use of the ambiguous  terms \"apparent size\" and \"perceived size\" without specifying the units of  measure has caused confusion.\n\n==Representation of visual angle in visual cortex==\nThe brain's [[primary visual cortex]] (area V1 or Brodmann area 17) contains a spatially [[isomorphic]] representation of the retina (see [[retinotopy]]).  Loosely speaking,  it is a distorted \"map\" of the retina. Accordingly, the size <math>R</math> of a given retinal image determines the extent of the neural activity pattern eventually generated in area V1 by the associated retinal activity pattern. Murray, Boyaci, & Kersten (2006) recently used [[Functional magnetic resonance imaging]]  (fMRI) to show that an increase in a viewed target's visual angle, which increases <math>R</math>, also increases the extent of the corresponding neural activity pattern in area V1.\n\nThe observers in Murray 'et al.'s' experiment viewed a flat picture with two discs that subtended the same visual angle <math>V</math> and formed retinal images of the same size <math>R</math>, but the perceived angular size <math>V'</math> of one was about 17% larger than for the other, due to differences in the background patterns for the disks. It was shown that the areas of the activity in V1 related to the disks were of unequal size, despite the fact that the retinal images were the same size.  This size difference in area V1 correlated with the 17% illusory difference between the perceived visual angles. This finding has implications for spatial illusions such as the [[visual angle illusion]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = An Analysis of the Experiment by Murray, S. O., Boyaci, H., & Kersten, D. (2006). \"The representation of perceived angular size in human primary visual cortex.\" | url = http://facstaff.uww.edu/mccreadd/appendixBB%20htm.htm | date = 5 February 2007 | work = The Moon Illusion Explained | first = Don | last = McCready | access-date = 7 December 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111207024436/http://facstaff.uww.edu/mccreadd/appendixBB%20htm.htm | archive-date = 7 December 2011 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Visual acuity]]\n*[[Visual angle illusion]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Baird, J. C. (1970).  ''Psychophysical analysis of visual space.'' Oxford, London: Pergamon Press.\n* Joynson, R. B. (1949). The problem of size and distance. ''Quarterly Journal of Experimental Psychology, 1'', 119\u2013135.\n* McCready, D. (1965). Size-distance perception and accommodation-convergence micropsia: A critique. ''Vision Research. 5,'' 189\u2013206.\n* McCready, D. (1985). On size, distance and visual angle perception. ''Perception & Psychophysics, 37'', 323\u2013334.\n* Murray, S.O., Boyaci, H, & Kersten, D. (2006) [https://web.archive.org/web/20150318052405/http://www.ski.org/Visproc/pdf/Murray-Boyaci-Kersten-2006.pdf The representation of perceived angular size in human primary visual cortex.] ''Nature Neuroscience, 9,'' 429\u2013434 (1 March 2006).\n* McCready, D. [https://web.archive.org/web/20151204212728/http://facstaff.uww.edu/mccreadd/ The Moon Illusion Explained].\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070403083855/http://www.smbs.buffalo.edu/oph/ped/IVAC/IVAC.html The University at Buffalo's Interactive Visual Acuity Chart] for the display of letters or symbols for a specified Snellen line on your computer monitor at exactly the right size (note: you must follow the instructions for calibration).\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Visual Angle}}\n[[Category:Vision]]\n[[Category:Angle]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_angle"}
{"title_page": "Vani Viswanath", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vani Viswanath\n| image              = \n| image_upright      = \n| native_name        = \u0d35\u0d3e\u0d23\u0d3f \u0d35\u0d3f\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d35\u0d28\u0d3e\u0d25\u0d4d\n| native_name_lang   = ml\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1971|5|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[Ollur]], [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]], India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 1989\u2013present\n| party              = [[Telugu Desam Party]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage |[[Baburaj (actor)|Baburaj]]|2002}}\n| mother             = Girija\n| father             = Thazhathuveettil Vishwanathan\n| children           = {{ubl|Aarcha, Adhri}}\n| awards             = {{Awd|[[Kerala State Film Awards]]|2000}}\n}}\n'''Vani Viswanath''' (born 13 May 1971) is an [[Indian film]] actress. She joined in [[Telugu Desam Party]] in [[Andhra Pradesh]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/mb4eves/online/malayalam/kerala/women/articles/infocus_interview-article-210230 |title=In Focus interview - Vani Viswanath |work=Mathrubhumi |access-date=11 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127015107/http://www.mathrubhumi.com/mb4eves/online/malayalam/kerala/women/articles/infocus_interview-article-210230 |archive-date=27 November 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2000, Vani won the [[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Actress]] for her performance in ''[[Susanna (2000 film)|Susanna]]'', directed by [[T. V. Chandran]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20010316/renews.htm|title=Kerala State Film Awards - 2000|date=16 March 2001|publisher=[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]]|accessdate=3 December 2009}}</ref> She was termed as [[Mollywood movie|Mollywood]]'s \"Action Queen\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article304239.ece |title=With guns blazing|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=2011-11-04}}</ref>  In 1986, she made her acticg debut through th e Mannukkul Vairam (1986)\n\n==Early life==\nVani was born as the fourth among the five children of [[Malayali]] parents Thazhathuveettil Vishwanathan, an astrologer and Girija, a housewife in [[Ollur]], [[Thrissur]] in 1971. When she was 13, her father predicted through astrology that she will become an actor and also she will enter into the politics.<ref>http://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies/interview/210231/</ref> Her mother hails from Ernakulam District and her father hails from Thrissur District.<ref>http://www.nostalgiamag.in/details.php?cat=&id=451</ref> She has four siblings.\n\nShe studied at [[Thrissur]] till fourth grade, later the family shifted to [[Madras]] and continued her education there till tenth grade. She got her first role while she was studying in tenth grade and hence she discontinued her studies and concentrated on her movie career.<ref>http://cinidiary.com/people.php?pigsection=Actor&picata=2&no_of_displayed_rows=40&no_of_rows_page=10&sletter=</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShe has appeared predominantly in [[Malayalam]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]] movies. She acted in ''[[The King (1995 film)|The King]]'' with [[Mammootty]]. She also appeared in Kannada and Tamil movies. She was among the big stars of her time in the [[South India]]. Her [[Telugu cinema|Tollywood]] movie ''[[Gharana Mogudu]]'' with Tollywood superstar, [[Chiranjeevi]] was a huge hit. Vani is trained in fighting and martial arts and has fought even several men bravely in the films. Vani also acted in two Hindi film with Superstar [[Mithun Chakraborty]] in ''[[Jung (1996 film)|Jung]]'' and ''[[Bhishma (1996 film)|Bhishma]]''.\n\n==Horse Riding Profession==\nVani was a professional horse rider before entering film. She won several horse riding competitions. At one time, she was considered to be India's No. 1 Women's jockey. She is also a famous Bullet motorcycle rider, who participated in several bullet races. She also has a [[Black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in [[Karate]].\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile acting for several films with [[Baburaj (actor)|Baburaj]], she fell in love with him. The couple got married in 2002 and have two children, Aarcha (born in 2002) and Adhri (born in 2008).<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0d07\u0d35\u0d3f\u0d1f\u0d46 \u0d0e\u0d32\u0d4d\u0d32\u0d3e\u0d35\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d38\u0d41\u0d16\u0d02 \u0d24\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d46..!|url=http://www.mangalam.com/women/personality/356025?page=0,4|publisher=mangalam.com|accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n;[[Kerala State Film Awards]]\n* 2000 - [[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Actress|Second Best Actress]] - ''[[Susanna (2000 film)|Susanna]]''\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Malayalam===\n{{colbegin|colwidth=22em}}\n# ''[[Mannar Mathai Speaking 2]]'' (2014) .... Lakshmi (Cameo)\n# ''[[Uppukandam Brothers Back In Action]]'' (2011) .... Kochamini\n# ''[[Black Dalia]]'' (2009)....IPS Officer Daisy Wilfred\n# ''Twenty :20'' (2008) ... Archive footage only\n# ''[[Chinthamani Kolacase]]'' (2006) .... Adv.Pattammal\n# ''[[Balram Vs Tharadas]]'' (2006) .... MLA Rani\n# ''[[Dany (film)|Danny]]'' (2002) .... Margarette\n# ''Bheri'' (2002) .... Vasudha Nedungadi\n# ''[[Akhila (film)|Akhila]]'' (2002) .... Akhila\n# ''[[Ee Bhargavee Nilayam]]'' (2002) .... Bhargavi\n# ''[[Ente Hridhayathinte Udama]]'' (2002) .... Uma\n# ''[[Puthooramputhri Unniyarcha]]'' (2002) .... Unniyarcha\n# ''[[India Gate (film)|India Gate]]'' (2002) ... IPS Officer\n# ''[[Nagaravadhu]]'' (2001) .... Sukanya\n# ''[[Ee Nadu Innalevare]]'' (2001).... Beena Benjamin IPS\n# ''[[Susanna (2000 film)|Susanna]]'' (2000) .... Susanna \n# ''[[Indriyam]]'' (2000) .... Neeli\n# ''[[Daivathinte Makan]]'' (2000)\n# ''[[Ival Draupathi]]'' (2000) .... Ajitha Madhavan\n# ''[[Rapid Action Force (film)|Rapid Action Force]]'' (2000)... Adithya Varma IPs\n# ''[[India Gate]]'' (2000).... Parvathi